nd":"Glasgow, Lanarkshire, Schotland","Callendar Park, Stirlingshire, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Callendar Park, Stirlingshire, Schotland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"6 July 1433–1 November 1472":"6 July 1433–1 November 1472","1430–1500":"1430–1500","1432–1497":"1432–1497","1433–1472":"1433–1472","1441–1493":"1441–1493","1446–1518":"1446–1518","1448–1483":"1448–1483","1455–1503":"1455–1503","1410–1467":"1410–1467","1410–1478":"1410–1478","1 November 1472":"1 November 1472","1483":"1483","1472":"1472","1493":"1493","1503":"1503","1448":"1448","1446":"1446","6 July 1433":"6 July 1433","1467":"1467","1478":"1478","1500":"1500","1455":"1455","1433":"1433","1410":"1410","1432":"1432","14 May 1434":"14 May 1434","1497":"1497","1441":"1441","1430":"1430","1518":"1518","Kilsyth, Stirlingshire, Scotland":"Kilsyth, Stirlingshire, Scotland","Glasgow, Lanarkshire, Scotland":"Glasgow, Lanarkshire, Scotland","Callendar Park, Stirlingshire, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Callendar Park, Stirlingshire, Scotland, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Livingston","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish: habitational name from a place in Lothian, originally named in Middle English as <i>Levingston</i>. The placename derives from the Middle English personal name <i>Leving</i> (genitive <i>Levinges</i>) + Middle English, Older Scots <i>toun</i> ‘town, village, settlement’.","Irish: surname adopted as equivalent of Gaelic <b>Ó Duinnshléibhe</b> and <b>Mac Duinnshléibhe</b> (see   Dunleavy  ).","Americanized form of Jewish   Lowenstein  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dunleavy","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Aidan, Connor, John Patrick, Siobhan.","Irish: shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Duinnshléibhe</b> or <b>Ó Duinnshléibhe</b> ‘son of <i>Donn Sléibhe</i>’, a personal name composed of the elements <i>donn</i> ‘brown-haired man’ or ‘chieftain’ + <i>sléibhe</i> ‘of the mountain’, meaning ‘chieftain (literally, brown one) of the mountain’."]},{"name":"Livingstone","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Livingston  ."]}]},{"name":"Alexander","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From the Latin form of the Greek name <i>Alexandros</i>, from <i>alexein</i> ‘to defend’ + <i>anēr</i> ‘man, warrior’ (genitive <i>andros</i>). The name became extremely popular in the post-classical period, and was borne by several individuals in the New Testament and some early Christian saints. Its use as a common given name throughout Europe, however, derives largely from the fame of  Alexander the Great , King of Macedon (  356–323  bc  ), around whom a large body of popular legend grew up in late antiquity, much of which came to be embodied in the medieval ‘Alexander romances’."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Alexander Livingston was born on 6 July 1433, in Kilsyth, Stirlingshire, Scotland, his father, James Livingston 1st Lord Livingston, was 24 and his mother, Marion Berwick, was 23. He had at least 1 son. He died on 1 November 1472, in Callendar Park, Stirlingshire, Scotland, United Kingdom, at the age of 39."},"et":{"6 July 1433–1 November 1472":"6. juuli 1433–1. november 1472","1430–1500":"1430–1500","1432–1497":"1432–1497","1433–1472":"1433–1472","1441–1493":"1441–1493","1446–1518":"1446–1518","1448–1483":"1448–1483","1455–1503":"1455–1503","1410–1467":"1410–1467","1410–1478":"1410–1478","1 November 1472":"1. november 1472","1483":"1483","1472":"1472","1493":"1493","1503":"1503","1448":"1448","1446":"1446","6 July 1433":"6. juuli 1433","1467":"1467","1478":"1478","1500":"1500","1455":"1455","1433":"1433","1410":"1410","1432":"1432","14 May 1434":"14. mai 1434","1497":"1497","1441":"1441","1430":"1430","1518":"1518","Kilsyth, Stirlingshire, Scotland":"Kilsyth, Stirlingshire, Scotland","Glasgow, Lanarkshire, Scotland":"Glasgow, Lanarkshire, Scotland","Callendar Park, Stirling